This paper deals with the analysis of structured time-series documents such as news articles and scientific papers, which involves the extraction of meaningful topics that evolve over time and are related to each other. This topic is relevant to several sub-categories of computer science, including computational linguistics (cs.CL), information retrieval (cs.IR), machine learning (cs.LG), social and information networks (cs.SI), and artificial intelligence (cs.DL). The paper's focus on topic modeling and its application to scientific papers suggests that cs.CL and cs.IR are the most likely sub-categories, followed by cs.LG, cs.SI, and cs.DL.
